"""
mkt-context | 1 Samuel | chapters 15–16 (fill)
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-15-16-fill.py

Covers 50 missing verses (ch15: 31 missing, ch16: 19 missing).
4 entries already present in each chapter — merge_comm will skip those.
Key decisions:
- Ch15: ḥērem institution and its history; Amalekite backdrop; Saul's selective obedience
- Ch16: Bethlehem and Jesse's family; anointing rituals in Israel and ANE;
         the rûaḥ (Spirit) departure theology; David as musician in the ancient world
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        existing.setdefault(ch, {})
        for v, html in verses.items():
            existing[ch].setdefault(v, html)

SAMUEL = {
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel's formal commission to Saul — 'YHWH sent me to anoint you king over his people Israel; now therefore listen to the words of YHWH' — restates the basis of Saul's authority (the prophetic anointing) as the ground of his obligation. The <em>šemaʿ</em> (listen/obey) verb that opens the commission sets up the <em>šāmaʿ</em>-theme of the chapter: hearing/obeying is the issue. The prophetic word frames the narrative: YHWH speaks through Samuel; the test is whether Saul will hear. The connection between anointing and obedience is constitutive of the Israelite monarchy.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The historical ground of the Amalek judgment: 'Thus says YHWH of hosts, I have noted what Amalek did to Israel in opposing them on the way when they came up out of Egypt.' The reference is to Exod 17:8-16 (the Amalek attack on Israel at Rephidim) and Deut 25:17-19 (the command to blot out Amalek's memory). The formulation <em>pāqadtî</em> (I have taken note of, I will punish) is the vocabulary of divine accounting: YHWH remembers and will act. The delay between the Exodus-era offense and the Saul-era execution shows that divine patience does not mean divine forgetting.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Saul mustered the people at Telaim — a site in the Negev region. The muster count (200,000 infantry and 10,000 men of Judah) follows the ANE convention of large round numbers for military census; the differentiation of Judah from Israel foreshadows the coming division of the monarchy. Telaim may be Telem of Josh 15:24 in southern Judah, positioning the assembled force near the Negev for a campaign against the Amalekites in that region.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul came to the city of Amalek and lay in wait in the valley. The military preparation — laying in wait (<em>wayya'āroḇ</em>) — uses the vocabulary of ambush tactics. The 'city of Amalek' is unidentified archaeologically, as Amalekites were semi-nomadic and their settlements were less permanent than Canaanite city-states. The campaign is in the Negev-Sinai region where Amalekite territory lay.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Kenite warning: 'Go, depart; go down from among the Amalekites, lest I destroy you with them. For you showed kindness to all the people of Israel when they came up out of Egypt.' The Kenites (associated with Jethro/Hobab, Moses's father-in-law; Judg 1:16) are historically distinguished from Amalekites and given prior warning. The <em>ḥesed</em> (covenant kindness) done to Israel at the Exodus is the reason for the exemption — the divine accounting that preserved Amalek's debt also preserves the Kenites' credit.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul struck Amalek from Havilah to Shur, which is east of Egypt. The geographic spread of the campaign: Havilah appears in Gen 25:18 as part of the area where Ishmael's descendants settled; Shur is the wilderness border region east of Egypt. The full sweep of the Amalekite territory from north Arabia to the Egyptian border is indicated, though only Saul's partial compliance will be narrated in what follows.</p>",
    "8": "<p>He took Agag the king of Amalek alive and devoted to destruction all the people with the edge of the sword. The capture of the Amalekite king Agag — rather than executing him under the <em>ḥērem</em> — is the first violation of the divine command. In ancient Near Eastern warfare, capturing the enemy king was a prize of war bringing honor and potentially ransom or trophy value; Saul's sparing of Agag likely reflects this ANE convention of royal treatment for royal prisoners. But the <em>ḥērem</em> command makes no exception for kings.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Saul and the people spared Agag and the best of the sheep and the oxen and the fattened calves and the lambs and all that was good, and would not utterly destroy them. The specific enumeration of what was spared — the best animals, the good things — reveals the selective nature of the disobedience: the <em>ḥērem</em> was applied to what was worthless but not to what had value. The <em>māʾăsû</em> (they refused/were unwilling) signals the intentional character of the failure to execute the ban.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The word of YHWH came to Samuel — the prophetic reception of the divine verdict before Samuel has any information from Saul. The narrative emphasizes that YHWH knew of the disobedience before Samuel did; the divine word comes to the prophet as a revelation, not a report. The immediate divine response to Saul's disobedience — before Saul even returns — shows the speed of the divine accounting.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Samuel rose early to meet Saul, and it was told to Samuel, 'Saul came to Carmel, and behold, he has set up a monument for himself and turned and passed on and gone down to Gilgal.' The <em>yāḏ</em> (hand/monument) Saul erects at Carmel before going to Gilgal is the first recorded instance of a royal victory monument in Israel — the kind of triumphal stele that Assyrian and Babylonian kings erected after victories. This detail characterizes Saul's orientation: his first act after the campaign is to commemorate himself, not offer thanks to YHWH.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Saul's greeting to Samuel — 'Blessed are you by YHWH; I have performed the commandment of YHWH' — is a false report. The formula <em>bārûḵ ʾattāh lADONAI</em> (blessed are you by/to YHWH) is a standard greeting of blessing; its use here to introduce a false claim about obedience highlights Saul's self-deception. He has rationalized his partial obedience as full obedience, and he greets the prophet with a pious formula while making a false claim about his faithfulness.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Samuel's rhetorical question — 'What then is this bleating of the sheep in my ears and the lowing of oxen that I hear?' — exposes the lie without accusation: the auditory evidence of Saul's disobedience is unmistakable. The device of the evidence speaking for itself (the animals' sounds) is a literary technique that allows Samuel to let the facts make the accusation before stating it explicitly. The question form puts Saul in the position of explaining what cannot be explained away.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Saul's first defense: 'They have brought them from the Amalekites, for the people spared the best of the sheep and of the oxen to sacrifice to YHWH your God, and the rest we have devoted to destruction.' The deflection onto 'the people' (<em>hāʿām</em>) is noted by the narrator with irony: in v9 both Saul and the people together spared them. The religious justification — sacrifice to YHWH — is the first instance of Saul using religious language to cover disobedience. The form 'YHWH your God' (rather than 'our God') is a subtle distancing from the God whose command he violated.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Samuel's command: 'Stop! I will tell you what YHWH said to me this night.' The rhetorical stop (<em>harap</em>, desist/be quiet) cuts off Saul's self-justification. Samuel's authority rests on direct prophetic revelation — 'what YHWH said to me this night' — which supersedes Saul's defensive rhetoric. The prophetic word received in the night is now to be delivered; the urgency and the timing ('this night') emphasize the immediacy of the divine response to Saul's failure.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samuel's confrontation begins with the historical reminder: 'Though you are little in your own eyes, are you not the head of the tribes of Israel? YHWH anointed you king over Israel.' The 'little in your own eyes' recalls Saul's initial humility before his anointing (1 Sam 9:21: 'Am I not a Benjaminite, from the least of the tribes of Israel?'); what was genuine humility has become false modesty that excuses disobedience. The anointing is invoked as the basis of responsibility — greater honor, greater accountability.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel recites the divine commission: 'YHWH sent you on a mission and said, Go, devote to destruction the sinners, the Amalekites, and fight against them until they are consumed.' The word <em>wᵉhaḥăramtāh</em> (you shall devote to destruction) is the verbal form of <em>ḥērem</em>; the commission is explicit and total. The Amalekites are characterized as <em>ḥaṭṭāʾîm</em> (sinners) — their guilt before YHWH is the basis of the <em>ḥērem</em>, not Israelite territorial ambition.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Samuel's direct accusation: 'Why then did you not obey the voice of YHWH? Why did you pounce on the spoil and do what was evil in the sight of YHWH?' The accusation names both failures: (1) not obeying (<em>šāmaʿ</em>) the divine voice, and (2) rushing on the spoil (<em>wāṭṭaʿaṭ ʾel-haššālāl</em>). The verb <em>ʿūṭ</em> (rush/pounce) used for attacking the spoil suggests rapacious eagerness. The double question frames the disobedience as both failure of listening and active transgression.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Saul's second defense repeats and expands the first: 'I have obeyed the voice of YHWH. I have gone on the mission on which YHWH sent me. I have brought Agag the king of Amalek, and I have devoted the Amalekites to destruction.' The threefold 'I have' (<em>ʾăšer šāmaʿtî... wāʾēlēḵ... wāʾābîʾ... wāʾaḥărēm</em>) is Saul's formal counter-claim. He asserts technical compliance — he performed the main action — while ignoring the specific exceptions. This is legal self-justification rather than repentance.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'But the people took of the spoil, sheep and oxen, the best of the things devoted to destruction, to sacrifice to YHWH your God at Gilgal.' The third deflection to 'the people' and the religious justification repeated (sacrifice to 'YHWH your God'). The religious framing of disobedience — using worship language to cover unauthorized action — is a pattern Samuel will address in v22. The specification of Gilgal as the sacrifice location is historically significant: Gilgal was the site of Saul's earlier partial disobedience (ch13:8-14).</p>",
    "23": "<p>Samuel's pronouncement on divination and idolatry as equivalents to rebellion: 'For rebellion is as the sin of divination, and presumption is as iniquity and idolatry.' The Hebrew terms: <em>merem kᵉḥaṭṭaʾt qesem</em> (rebellion like the sin of divination) and <em>wᵉhapaṣar kᵉʾāwen ûtᵉrāpîm</em> (stubbornness like iniquity and idols/teraphim). The comparison of disobedience to the Deuteronomically prohibited practices of divination and idol-worship places Saul's sin in the gravest category: not ritual error but structural apostasy. Because you have rejected the word of YHWH, he has rejected you as king.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Saul's confession — 'I have sinned, for I have transgressed the commandment of YHWH and your words, because I feared the people and obeyed their voice' — acknowledges the sin but identifies 'fear of the people' as the cause. The <em>yārēʾtî ʾet-hāʿām</em> (I feared the people) places the decisive weight on human approval rather than divine command. This is Saul's self-diagnosis and the narrator's understanding: the king who feared the people more than YHWH failed the test of covenant leadership.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Saul's request: 'Please pardon my sin and return with me, that I may bow before YHWH.' The request for forgiveness (<em>śā nāʾ ʾet-ḥaṭṭāʾtî</em>, please lift/carry my sin) uses the standard vocabulary of forgiveness. But Samuel's response (v26) denies the request — not because forgiveness is impossible but because the consequences of Saul's rejection are already set: 'YHWH has rejected you from being king over Israel.' The forgiveness of the individual sin and the removal of the kingdom are distinct.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Samuel's refusal: 'I will not return with you. For you have rejected the word of YHWH, and YHWH has rejected you from being king over Israel.' The structural parallelism: Saul's rejection of YHWH's word (<em>māʾastā</em>) is met by YHWH's rejection of Saul (<em>wayyimʾāsᵉḵā</em>). The verb <em>māʾas</em> (reject/despise) appears in both directions; the legal principle of reciprocal rejection — those who reject YHWH are rejected by YHWH — is the theological hinge of the narrative.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Saul seized the hem of Samuel's robe and it tore. The robe-hem (<em>kānāp̄</em>) of a garment was associated with identity and authority in the ancient Near East; seizure of a garment hem was a gesture of entreaty. In Akkadian legal practice, grasping the hem of the creditor's robe was a gesture of supplication. The tearing of the hem as Saul grasps at Samuel is a sign-act that Samuel immediately interprets as a prophetic symbol (v28) of the tearing of the kingdom from Saul.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Samuel interprets the torn robe: 'YHWH has torn the kingdom of Israel from you this day and has given it to a neighbor of yours, who is better than you.' The torn garment as prophetic symbol of divided/transferred kingship has an exact parallel in 1 Kgs 11:30-31, where Ahijah tears his garment into 12 pieces to symbolize the division of Solomon's kingdom. The 'neighbor of yours, who is better than you' (<em>lᵉrēʿăḵā haṭṭôḇ mimmekā</em>) points forward to David — though David is not named here, the next narrative introduces him as YHWH's chosen.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'The Glory of Israel will not lie or have regret, for he is not a man, that he should have regret.' The divine epithet <em>nēṣaḥ yiśrāʾēl</em> (Everlasting of Israel / Glory of Israel) is rare and distinctive. The statement that God does not <em>niḥam</em> (relent/regret) here appears to contradict v11 where God 'regrets' making Saul king. The solution lies in the distinction: YHWH can grieve over human outcomes (v11) without reversing his judicial decisions (v29). The relenting of v11 is emotional; the not-relenting of v29 is about the finality of the royal rejection.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Saul's third request: 'I have sinned; yet honor me now before the elders of my people and before Israel, and return with me, that I may bow before YHWH your God.' The request to be honored publicly before the elders reveals Saul's persisting preoccupation with social standing. He acknowledges the sin but his primary concern is not restoration with YHWH but preservation of his public image. The 'honor me' (<em>kabbᵉdēnî nāʾ</em>) request and the 'YHWH your God' formula (still distancing) characterize the depth of Saul's problem.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Samuel turned back after Saul, and Saul bowed before YHWH. Samuel's return with Saul is a concession to the public context — he does not abandon Saul publicly — but it does not reverse the prophetic judgment of rejection. The bowing before YHWH is the last act of official worship by the rejected king; the remainder of the chapter will be Samuel's execution of the <em>ḥērem</em> judgment that Saul failed to complete.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Samuel said, 'Bring here to me Agag the king of Amalek.' Agag came to him cheerfully. The characterization of Agag's approach as 'cheerfully' (<em>maʿăḏannōṯ</em> — or alternatively 'haltingly/trembling'; the Hebrew is contested) is ironic. Agag apparently believes that having survived the battle and been spared by Saul, his life is secure. His next words confirm he expects mercy: 'Surely the bitterness of death is past.'</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Surely the bitterness of death is past' — Agag's statement is either confidence (death has passed me by) or recognition that death is near ('the bitterness of death is at hand'). Samuel's response — 'As your sword has made women childless, so shall your mother be childless among women' — invokes the <em>lex talionis</em> principle: the childlessness Amalek caused to Israelite families is now visited on Agag's mother. Samuel hewed Agag to pieces before YHWH at Gilgal — the execution site is where Saul had offered the unauthorized sacrifice (ch13).</p>",
    "34": "<p>Samuel went to Ramah and Saul went up to his house at Gibeah of Saul. The parting is final and geographical: Samuel to Ramah (his home), Saul to Gibeah (his capital). The separation is enacted spatially. Samuel and Saul will meet one more time (1 Sam 19:24 — Saul at Naioth) and once posthumously via necromancy at Endor (ch28). The separation of prophet and king marks the unraveling of the Saulide monarchy — the king without a prophet is the king without a word from YHWH.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "2": "<p>Samuel's objection: 'How can I go? If Saul hears it, he will kill me.' Samuel's fear reveals the political danger of anointing a new king while Saul lives. The threat of royal execution for prophets is attested in the Elijah-Jezebel narratives (1 Kgs 19:2) and in Jeremiah's experience (Jer 26:20-23). YHWH's response — take a heifer as a cover story for visiting Bethlehem for a sacrifice — is a form of protective concealment, raising interesting questions about deception for protective purposes that Jewish and Christian interpreters have long discussed.</p>",
    "3": "<p>YHWH's instructions to Samuel at Bethlehem: 'Invite Jesse to the sacrifice, and I will show you what you shall do. And you shall anoint for me him whom I declare to you.' The withholding of the specific name until the moment of selection — YHWH will reveal the anointed one at the sacrifice, not in advance — maintains the narrative suspense and establishes that the selection is entirely YHWH's. The formula <em>wᵉʾet ʾăšer ʾōmar ʾēlêḵā tāšûr</em> (the one whom I tell you, him you shall anoint) is the prophetic commission in its most concise form.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Samuel came to Bethlehem, and the elders of the city came to meet him trembling. The trembling (<em>wayeḥᵉrᵉḏû</em>) of the Bethlehem elders at Samuel's arrival reflects his dual role as prophet and judge: prophetic visitations could mean both blessing and judgment. Samuel's reassurance — 'I come peacefully; I have come to sacrifice to YHWH' — uses the peace formula (<em>šālôm</em>) that distinguishes a visit of blessing from one of judgment. The elders' fear and Samuel's reassurance establish the social setting of the anointing.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Samuel consecrated Jesse and his sons and invited them to the sacrifice. The consecration (<em>qiddēš</em>) required ritual preparation — washing, changing garments, abstaining from sexual relations (cf. Exod 19:10-15 for the Sinai paradigm) — before approaching YHWH in sacrifice. The invitation of Jesse's household to the sacrificial meal provides the cover within which the anointing will occur. The sequence: public sacrifice (cover story), private divine selection (the real purpose).</p>",
    "6": "<p>When they came, Samuel saw Eliab and thought, 'Surely the LORD's anointed is before him.' Samuel's first impression — that Eliab, the eldest son, must be the one — is the human default toward primogeniture and physical impression. Eliab is apparently physically impressive (implied by the correction in v7). Samuel's error here is the error of every human observer who sees with external eyes: the height and appearance that initially recommended Saul (1 Sam 9:2: 'there was not a man among the people of Israel more handsome than he') misled Samuel then too.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abinadab passed before Samuel and Samuel said, 'Neither has YHWH chosen this one.' The second rejection. The narrative economy of the seven rejections — each noted briefly — creates a rhythmic pattern that builds anticipation for the eighth. The formula 'YHWH has not chosen this one' (<em>gam bāzeh lōʾ bāḥar YHWH</em>) is the divine negative that will be reversed only when the unexpected seventh/eighth son is presented.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shammah passed and Samuel said, 'Neither has YHWH chosen this one.' The third rejection. The enumeration of Jesse's sons in 1 Chr 2:13-15 lists David as the seventh son (not eighth as sometimes calculated here); the difference may reflect a son who died without issue. The sequential review of the sons before their father and the prophet gives the scene the character of a formal presentation — a court introduction, almost a parade of candidates.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jesse made seven of his sons pass before Samuel, and Samuel said to Jesse, 'YHWH has not chosen these.' The summary of seven rejections before the question about remaining sons establishes the contrast: YHWH's choice will not be among the expected candidates. The number seven is complete; the next will be beyond the expected sequence. The pattern of election beyond the expected order — younger over older — runs through Israel's narrative (Isaac over Ishmael, Jacob over Esau, Ephraim over Manasseh, Judah over Reuben).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Samuel's question: 'Are all your sons here?' Jesse's answer: 'There remains yet the youngest, but behold, he is keeping the sheep.' The word <em>haqqāṭān</em> (the youngest/smallest) echoes Samuel's earlier address to Saul about being 'small in your own eyes' (v15:17) and Benjamin being 'the smallest tribe.' The youngest, tending sheep — the most marginalized member of the family, given the task appropriate for the youngest and least — is the one YHWH has chosen. Samuel's response: 'Send and get him, for we will not sit down till he comes here.'</p>",
    "12": "<p>The description of David: 'He was ruddy (<em>ʾadmônî</em>), and had beautiful eyes (<em>yᵉpēh ʿênayim</em>), and was handsome (<em>ṭôḇ rōʾî</em>).' The three physical descriptors — ruddy complexion, beautiful eyes, handsome appearance — ironically describe physical attractiveness despite the principle just stated in v7 (YHWH looks at the heart, not outward appearance). The resolution: YHWH is not anti-physical beauty; the point of v7 is that physical appearance is not the criterion of election, not that it is absent from the chosen. David is handsome, but he is not chosen for that.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Saul's servants describe the troubled spirit and propose a solution: 'Let our lord command your servants who are before you to seek out a man who is skillful in playing the lyre, and when the evil spirit from God is upon you, he will play it, and you will be well.' The therapeutic use of music — specifically stringed instruments — as treatment for emotional or spiritual disturbance is attested in ancient Near Eastern medical texts. The Mesopotamian tradition included 'incantation priests' who combined music and verbal formulas for healing; the Israelite practice here is stripped of incantation but retains the music therapy element.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Saul's agreement: 'Provide for me a man who can play well and bring him to me.' The king's receptivity to the musical cure is the narrative mechanism that brings David to court. The request is for musical skill (<em>yōdēaʿ mᵉnaggēn</em>, one who knows how to play), not for spiritual insight or prophetic gift. Saul in his degraded state needs a musician; YHWH in his providence provides the one on whom the Spirit rests — more than Saul asked for.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul to his servants: 'Provide for me a man who can play well and bring him to me.' The king's court required skilled musicians: ancient Near Eastern royal courts, including Assyrian and Egyptian ones, maintained professional musicians among their staff. The court musician was a recognized social role; David's entry into Saul's service as a musician is consistent with ANE court practice.</p>",
    "18": "<p>One of the young men described David: 'I have seen a son of Jesse the Bethlehemite, who is skillful in playing, a man of valor, a man of war, prudent in speech, and a man of good presence, and YHWH is with him.' The sixfold description is remarkable: musical skill + military valor + combat experience + wisdom in speech + good appearance + divine presence. The accumulation of qualities presents David as the complete leader. The final qualification — 'YHWH is with him' (<em>waYHWH ʿimmô</em>) — is the theological summary that distinguishes David from all previous candidates.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Saul sent messengers to Jesse: 'Send me David your son, who is with the sheep.' The identification of David through his pastoral occupation — with the sheep — connects the anointing narrative with the call narratives of other leaders who were working when called (Moses tending Jethro's flock at the burning bush, Exod 3:1; Elisha plowing with 12 yoke of oxen when Elijah called him, 1 Kgs 19:19-20). The shepherd who becomes king is a topos in ancient Near Eastern royal ideology; Hammurabi calls himself the 'shepherd of the people' in his law code prologue.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jesse sent David to Saul with a donkey loaded with bread, a skin of wine, and a young goat as a gift. The gift (<em>minḥāh</em>) accompanying a request for royal service follows ANE protocol for approaching a king or great man (cf. 1 Sam 9:7-8, Saul's gift to Samuel). The specific provisions — bread, wine, goat — are the standard components of a formal gift presentation. Jesse's generous gift reflects the social honor of his son being requested for royal service.</p>",
    "21": "<p>David came to Saul and entered his service. Saul loved him greatly, and David became his armor-bearer. The office of armor-bearer (<em>nōśēʾ kēlîm</em>, carrier of weapons) was a position of trust and proximity to the king in battle — the armor-bearer fought alongside and protected the king. Jonathan's armor-bearer famously fought with him at Michmash (1 Sam 14:6-14); Saul's armor-bearer refused to kill his master at Gilboa (1 Sam 31:4-5). The office is an honorable military appointment that places David within arm's reach of the king.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul sent to Jesse: 'Let David remain in my service, for he has found favor in my sight.' The favor-formula (<em>māṣāʾ ḥēn bᵉʿênay</em>) is the standard phrase for royal approval of a courtier (cf. Gen 39:4, Joseph finding favor in Potiphar's sight; Esth 2:9, Esther finding favor in the house-warden's sight). Saul's official request to retain David constitutes a formal appointment to royal service. Jesse's son has gone from the pasture to the palace through the chain of providential events set in motion by the anointing.</p>",
    "23": "<p>When the evil spirit from God was upon Saul, David took the lyre and played it with his hand. Saul would be refreshed and well, and the evil spirit would depart from him. The efficacy of David's music in relieving Saul's distress is presented without rationalistic explanation: the narrative simply reports the effect. The therapeutic function of music in antiquity is well-attested (the Egyptian papyrus Ebers recommends vocal incantations for healing; Assyrian exorcism rituals used musical accompaniment); what is distinctive here is that the benefit comes through the one on whom the Spirit of YHWH rests — the Spirit-anointed musician brings <em>rûaḥ</em>-relief to the Spirit-abandoned king.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1samuel')
    merge_comm(existing, SAMUEL)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1samuel', existing)
    for ch in ['15', '16']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
